2
00:00:17,108 --> 00:00:39,932
Road Runner: our cleanest result.
The fast model alone cannot score — it has the reflexes but doesn't
know which direction to commit.

3
00:00:53,442 --> 00:01:19,170
Ms.
Pacman: our original headline.
Fast scores 256.

4
00:01:29,776 --> 00:01:53,848
River Raid: the largest latent-text gap in our entire sweep — 82
percent.
Initial training showed the bridges collapsing.

5
00:02:04,910 --> 00:02:21,374
Seaquest: 80 versus 63 — a 26 percent latent advantage.
The latent policy is fully deterministic, locked into an eight-kill
exploit pattern.

6
00:02:41,244 --> 00:03:14,532
Q*bert reveals an exception to the bandwidth claim.
Q*bert's strategy is fundamentally categorical — jump up-right to tile
three-two.

7
00:03:17,578 --> 00:03:50,912
Space Invaders gave us our most important methodology finding.
All three knob-tuning attempts — random data, expert data, aggressive
prompts — produced text and latent scores of zero, while fast alone

8
00:03:53,912 --> 00:04:09,296
Enduro: smaller absolute scores because the underlying SB3 expert was
weak, but the latent-over-text pattern still holds.
Latent 5.8, text 4.9 — an 18 percent gap.

9
00:04:27,246 --> 00:04:50,262
Across seven games, the latent bridge beats the text bridge by 18 to
82 percent on continuous-content games, and loses to text only on the
categorical exception, Q*bert.

